  "opinion": "As a 18-year-old fitness trainer in Naples, I’ve seen how science and health intersect in daily life, but I’m not sure I fully grasp the gender gap in science. From what I’ve observed, the gap isn’t just about fewer women in labs—it’s deeper. In my part-time job, I work with people who often assume men are naturally better at math or physics, which is a stereotype that’s been passed down through generations. My parents, one of whom has a bachelor’s degree, taught me that science is for everyone, but society still tells girls they’re not cut out for it. I think the gender gap in science is a systemic issue rooted in childhood education and cultural expectations. For example, in my town, girls are often steered toward nursing or teaching, while boys are pushed toward engineering or computer science. That’s not fair. We should address it by changing how we teach science from an early age. Schools need to have more hands-on activities for girls, like coding clubs or biology labs, to show them that science isn’t just for boys. Also, mentors who are women in STEM fields could inspire more girls to pursue these careers. But it’s not just about schools—it’s about changing the way society views science. I’ve noticed that on social media, women in science often have to fight for recognition, which shows how much bias still exists. Addressing this gap isn’t just about fairness; it’s about progress. If we want better science for everyone, we need to give girls the same opportunities as boys. As someone who values mental health and enjoys hiking and knitting, I believe that everyone has the potential to contribute to science, and we should help them realize it.",
